issue.body:
Good morning! In our application, we have a LINQ to SQL tree like the following:

```C#
var primaryList = db.Customers.Where(c => c.CompanyName.ToLower().Contains(query))
                                .OrderByDescending(x => x.CompanyName.ToLower().StartsWith(query)))
                             .Take(50)
                             .AsSplitQuery()
                             .Select(x => new CustomerViewModel(x)) //
                             .ToList();
```

Before our upgrade to .NET 8, this query would get matching customers and have the ones whose names started with the query at top. For example, "Frank" would return "Frank's Catering", "Frank & Sons Construction", "John Frank Tax Consultant"; the use case that matters more here is when there are no customers who StartWith the given query, such as when "Police" returns "Local Town Police Station", "Other Local Town Police Department", "State Police Museum" and so on. After the upgrade, with no changes to the queries, Frank now only returns "Frank's Catering" and "Frank & Sons Construction", and "Police" returns zero results.

### Replication steps:
Given a table for an ExampleEntity that has at least one StringProperty, set up a query such as:
```C#
var query = "test";
var results = db.ExampleEntities.OrderBy(x => x.StringProperty.ToLower().Contains(query)).ToList();
//Expected results: All entities on that table, with the ones whose StringProperty contains "test" on top.
//Actual results on my machine: Same as expected results.

var otherQuery = "test";
var otherResults = db.ExampleEntities.OrderBy(x => x.StringProperty.ToLower().StartsWith(query)).ToList();
//Expected results: All entities on that table, with the ones whose StringProperty starts with "test" on top.
//Actual results on my machine: Only the entities on that table whose StringProperty starts with "test" with all others excluded. 
```

### Currently implemented workaround:
For the time being, we will be working around this by removing the StartsWith method from the ordering logic.

### Include provider and version information

EF Core version: 8.0.0
Database provider: "Microsoft SQL Server Express (64-bit)" running on "Windows Server 2022 Standard (10.0)" accessed in code via the "Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore" package.
Target framework:  .NET 8.0
Operating system: Windows 11
IDE: Visual Studio 2022 17.8.0
